FEW-SHOT EXAMPLE — How a P&R engineer reasons through one ECO iteration.
Real path from an ibex/ASAP7 run. Demonstrates the THINKING, not the result.
Use this as a template — follow the same step sequence on the iteration_context
you will be given below this example.

## STEP 1 — Establish the failure
Always read these scalars first. They frame the entire iteration.

  wns_slack_ps      = -285.55       # worst setup slack we must close
  tns_ps            = -328105       # total negative slack — TNS reductions
                                      compound across all violating endpoints
  clock_period_ps   = 700           # baseline budget
  num_violating_endpoints = 5       # we get top-5 paths in path[]

Setup-slack target each iter: improve WNS by 1-5ps WITHOUT degrading TNS by
more than the WNS gain × num_endpoints. A move that fixes WNS by +3 but
pushes 4 other endpoints down 2ps each is a net loss.

## STEP 2 — Enumerate the top-5 paths and check for shared prefix
From the path[] block we look at the startpoint of each path and the first
few stages. If multiple paths share the early cells, one move on a shared
stage helps multiple endpoints — highest leverage.

  path1: slack=-285.55 startpoint=if_stage_i.instr_rdata_id_o[16]/QN  endpoint=instr_addr_o[21]
  path2: slack=-284.74 startpoint=if_stage_i.instr_rdata_id_o[16]/QN  endpoint=instr_addr_o[28]
  path3: slack=-284.21 startpoint=if_stage_i.instr_rdata_id_o[16]/QN  endpoint=instr_addr_o[19]
  path4: slack=-283.95 startpoint=if_stage_i.instr_rdata_id_o[15]/QN  endpoint=instr_addr_o[11]
  path5: slack=-283.10 startpoint=if_stage_i.instr_rdata_id_o[16]/QN  endpoint=instr_addr_o[29]

Observation: 4 of 5 paths share startpoint instr_rdata_id_o[16]/QN.
on_other_violating_paths column in path[] confirms which stages are shared.
Stages with on_other_violating_paths >= 3 = shared by most paths = leverage.
A move on such a stage scales by ~4x: one +2ps fix helps 4 violating endpoints.

## STEP 2.5 — Familiarize with the <cell_delay_reference> block
Before doing any arithmetic, recognize that the system prompt contains a
<cell_delay_reference> block listing Liberty NLDM cell_delay and out_slew
data for every combinational cell in this technology. ALWAYS look up the
actual numbers from this table instead of guessing scaling ratios.

Reading the table:
  - Each cell has a "drive ladder" line showing all sizes within a VT.
    E.g. `SL drive ladder: x2(ic=0.566) → x3(ic=0.677) → ...`
  - Per-cell rows show: `<cell>_<VT> is=<slew>: d1/s1 d2/s2 d3/s3 d4/s4`
    where the 4 columns correspond to load=[1.5, 5, 15, 40] ff.
  - To estimate at YOUR stage's (load, slew) point: locate the nearest
    two slew rows and nearest two load columns, bilinearly interpolate.
  - For VT swap predictions: compare same drive (e.g. x6f) across L/R/SL.

Use the reference table for ALL Δcell_delay and Δout_slew predictions in
the cascade arithmetic of Step 5 — never guess.

## STEP 2.6 — Familiarize with <nearby_endpoints> and <shared_cells_to_nearby>
Below path[] you have two MORE blocks the model MUST consult before any
move that perturbs upstream load (resize, clone, buffer insert/remove):

  nearby_endpoints[N]{rank, startpoint, endpoint, slack_ps, n_shared_with_top5}:
    Ranks 6..50 — paths just outside the top-5 window. The slack column
    shows how close each is to becoming the new WNS.

  shared_cells_to_nearby[M]{inst, n_nearby_paths, nearby_path_ranks, worst_nearby_slack_ps}:
    Per top-5 instance that also appears on nearby paths — the cascade graph.
    If you touch that inst, those nearby paths get perturbed.

Use these to predict sibling-tip risk:
  - Look up your candidate instance X in shared_cells_to_nearby.
  - If X has worst_nearby_slack_ps within 3 ps of WNS, your move risks
    tipping that path. Compare your predicted ΔWNS gain on the targeted
    path vs the potential loss on the worst nearby before committing.
  - Example: WNS=-78.5. X appears on nearby paths [6,8,12] with
    worst_nearby_slack_ps=-76.5 (2 ps headroom). If your upsize gains
    +2.0 ps on the targeted path BUT pushes path 6 down by -3 ps, you are
    creating a new WNS at -79.5 ps. Net loss.

Iter-3 and iter-10 regressions on prior runs were exactly this pattern.

## STEP 3 — Walk path 1 stage-by-stage; flag the large delays AND removal candidates
Two parallel scans:

  (i) Flag large-delay stages: cell_delay_ps > 15 OR wire_delay_ps > 5.
      These need resize / VT swap / structural attention.

  (ii) Flag REMOVAL CANDIDATES: any BUFx*/INVx* with
       load_cap_ff < 2.0 AND cell_delay_ps > 10 AND fanout <= 2.
      These are buffers whose own delay exceeds what their removal would cost
      upstream. Regardless of name prefix (place*, rebuffer*, output*, eco_*).
      Output-port buffers (output*) almost always qualify — they exist for
      synthesis hygiene, not load-bearing reasons.

Rule: flag any stage where cell_delay_ps > 15 OR wire_delay_ps > 5.
Sample rows (path[] gives 67 stages for this path; below are the early ones):

stage  driver_pin              cell                     fanout  load_ff  wire_cap  in_slew  out_slew  cell_d  wire_d  wire_len  oovp  vt_swap_avail
1.1   instr_rdata_id_o[16]/QN  DFFHQNx3_ASAP7_75t_SL     4      6.07     0.54      20.9     31.03     50.88   0.23    2.16      4    -                 # DFF, dont_touch — skip
1.2   place7071/Y              BUFx6f_ASAP7_75t_SL       6      11.57    4.84      31.04    17.21     18.75   5.98    18.14     4    -                 # ← LARGE wire_delay AND cell_delay
1.3   place7069/Y              BUFx8_ASAP7_75t_SL        10     17.17    8.01      24.85    21.73     23.34   11.57   29.43     4    -                 # ← VERY LARGE wire, fanout=10
1.4   place7068/Y              BUFx6f_ASAP7_75t_SL       4      3.70     0.77      41.9     9.5       18.54   0.57    3.24      4    -                 # ← input slew is HUGE (41.9ps)
1.5   place7067/Y              BUFx3_ASAP7_75t_SL        7      5.53     2.24      9.65     14.7      16.03   1.02    6.70      4    -                 # ← upsize available, fanout=7
1.6   _31346_/Y                OA211x2_ASAP7_75t_SL      1      0.73     0.10      14.92    12.5      26.74   0.04    0.27      4    -                 # ← LARGE cell_d at tiny load
1.7   _31347_/Y                OR3x4_ASAP7_75t_SL        1      0.81     0.20      12.5     15.53     29.56   0.09    0.76      4    -                 # ← LARGE cell_d at tiny load
1.8   _31348_/Y                AND3x2_ASAP7_75t_L        1      1.97     1.36      15.53    9.99      18.28   0.50    8.37      4    SL@0.638          # ← L-VT, swap candidate
1.11  _31350_/Y                INVx1_ASAP7_75t_L         2      1.27     0.20      13.81    13.55     10.02   0.11    1.08      4    SL@0.667          # ← L-VT, swap candidate
1.12  _19545_/Y                AO22x1_ASAP7_75t_L        1      0.66     0.14      13.55    10.89     17.18   0.06    0.70      4    SL@0.455          # ← L-VT, swap candidate

## STEP 4 — For each flagged stage, diagnose WHY it is slow
Classify the cause: wire-dominated, cell-dominated, slew-cascade, oversized,
or VT-driven. The diagnosis dictates the move type.

Stage 1.2 (place7071/Y BUFx6f, cell_d=18.75, wire_d=5.98, wire_len=18.14um):
  - wire_d/cell_d = 0.32 → cell-dominated by ratio
  - BUT 18um wire + load_cap 11.57ff at fanout 6 says wire is a real factor
  - in_slew is 31ps (high) and out_slew is 17 (improved by driver) — driver IS doing work
  - DIAGNOSIS: cell-dominated; current driver is BUFx6f, upsize options are
    BUFx8/10/12/12f/16f available in the upsize column (input_caps 0.915/1.302/1.301/2.532/2.533).

Stage 1.3 (place7069/Y BUFx8, fanout=10, load=17.17ff, wire_d=11.57ps, wire_len=29.43um):
  - wire_d > cell_d → WIRE-DOMINATED
  - load_cap 17.17ff at fanout=10 + 29um wire run
  - DIAGNOSIS: wire-dominated. Two viable moves:
      (a) eco_clone_gate_worst_half: split fanout 10 → 5+5, each branch with shorter wire
      (b) eco_insert_buffer: break the 29um net at its midpoint
    Compute which is cheaper (see Step 5/6).

Stage 1.4 (place7068/Y BUFx6f, in_slew=41.9ps, out_slew=9.5ps):
  - in_slew is 41.9ps — the UPSTREAM driver (stage 1.3) is feeding a very slow edge
  - this stage's cell_delay (18.54) is inflated BECAUSE of the slow in_slew
  - DIAGNOSIS: SLEW-CASCADE. Do NOT touch stage 1.4. Fix stage 1.3 (the slew-source).

Stage 1.6 (_31346_/Y OA211x2_SL, cell_d=26.74, load=0.73ff, fanout=1):
  - load is tiny, fanout=1, yet cell_delay is huge
  - in_slew was 14.92ps (normal) and out_slew is 12.5 (low) — not slew-cascaded
  - This is an OA211x2 of size 2 already; no further upsize without changing cell type
  - load=0.73ff is so small that upsizing the DRIVER won't help — the cell delay
    formula is roughly Tcell ≈ K1 + K2*Cload. K2*Cload is small here, so the
    intrinsic K1 dominates. Upsizing the cell increases K2 but only marginally helps K1.
  - DIAGNOSIS: cell-intrinsic-limited. Marginal-return move — DEFER.

Stage 1.8/1.11/1.12 (_31348_, _31350_, _19545_  ending in _L):
  - L-VT (Low-Vth) variants. Slower than SL because L is the "leakage-low" corner.
    naming convention in ASAP7: SL = Super-Low-Vth (fastest), L = Low-Vth (medium),
    R = Regular-Vth (slowest). So L is SLOWER than SL.
  - vt_swap column shows the SL variant is available (AND3x2_SL@0.638, INVx1_SL@0.667 etc.)
  - Δinput_cap of swap is < 5% — upstream sees negligible additional load
  - DIAGNOSIS: VT-driven. eco_resize_gate to the SL variant. Cheapest move available;
    reliable 2-5ps gain per swap with near-zero cascade. Always try VT swaps first.

New diagnostic category — slew-source-with-unfixable-upstream:
  A stage qualifies when ALL of the following hold:
    - This stage's out_slew_ps is anomalously large (>50 ps is a strong
      signal; >80 ps almost always qualifies) given its load_cap_ff.
      Compare to <cell_delay_reference>'s out_slew at this cell's (load, is)
      row — if reality is 2x+ higher than reference, the cell is pumping
      a degraded edge that won't self-clean.
    - This stage's cell's upstream remedies are EXHAUSTED:
        upsize=[] (no bigger drive variant in the lib for this cell type)
        AND vt_swap=[] (already at the fastest VT, or no swap available)
        AND the cell is unmodifiable for structural reasons (e.g. an adder
        primitive — FA*, HA* — that synthesis won't allow restructuring).
    - At least ONE downstream stage in the next 1-3 stages shows
      cell_delay much larger than its Liberty (load, is=10ps) baseline,
      i.e. its delay is inflated by the bad in_slew arriving from here.
      Quantify: lookup downstream cell at (its load, is=10 ps) in
      <cell_delay_reference>; compare to its current cell_delay_ps in
      path[]. Gap > 10 ps is significant; gap > 20 ps is large.
  DIAGNOSIS: SLEW-SOURCE — candidate for SLEW-CLEANUP buffer insertion on
  the net between this stage and the next downstream cell. The buffer
  reads the bad slew, drives a clean edge into the slew-sensitive
  downstream chain, and recovers the inflated cell_delay there.
  This is the ONE case where eco_insert_buffer is justified despite
  the wire being short — the savings come from downstream slew
  sensitivity, not wire shortening. See Candidate H in Step 5 for math.

## STEP 5 — For each candidate move, do the cascade arithmetic
An engineer never touches a cell without computing what the move does to:
  A. The target stage's own delay (what we're trying to reduce)
  B. The upstream driver's load (input_cap delta scales the upstream delay)
  C. The path's wire delay (only changes for clone/buffer/remove, not for resize)
  D. The slew downstream (a faster driver feeds a faster edge to the next stage)

CANDIDATE A: eco_resize_gate place7071 BUFx8_ASAP7_75t_SL  (1.2: BUFx6f → BUFx8)
  A. Δcell_delay on stage 1.2 — LOOK UP in <cell_delay_reference>:
     Stage operating point: load_cap_ff=11.57, in_slew_ps=31.04 (from path[]).
     BUFx6f_SL ic=1.297:
       is=10: 8.1/9   11.0/15   17.2/26  ...
       is=30: 11.0/12 13.3/17   19.5/27  ...   ← look here (is~30)
     For load 11.57 between 5 and 15 ff: interpolate ~12.6 ps delay, ~16ps slew.
     BUFx8_SL ic=0.915 same row (is=30): 9.8/12 12.6/16 ...
     Bilinear at load=11.57, is=31: ~11.3 ps delay, ~14 ps slew.
     → Δcell_delay = 11.3 − 12.6 = -1.3 ps  (slightly less than naive "−3ps")
     Liberty-accurate prediction; do NOT guess scaling ratios.
  B. Upstream load delta:
     Look up input_caps from the SL drive ladder for BUF:
       x6f ic=1.297, x8 ic=0.915 → Δic = -0.382 ff (cap-DECREASING upsize)
     Upstream stage 1.1 (DFFHQNx3_SL) sees that drop → its delay also drops
     slightly. Estimate +0.3 ps upstream (DFF is robust to small load changes).
  C. Wire delay unchanged (same net, same routing, no new instances).
  D. out_slew: 16ps → 14ps (Liberty lookup). Next stage 1.3 (in_slew=24.85ps
     → ~22ps post-fix) sees slightly cleaner edge; downstream cell delay
     drops by ~0.5 ps.
  Net Δslack: +1.3 + 0.3 + 0.5 = +2.1 ps on path 1 (LIBERTY-DERIVED estimate)
  Shared-prefix: on_other_violating_paths = 4 → effective TNS gain ~8 ps
  E. SIBLING-TIP CHECK — look up `place7071` in shared_cells_to_nearby:
     if entry exists with worst_nearby_slack_ps near WNS (e.g. -76.5 when
     WNS=-78.5), this upsize might shift the upstream load just enough to
     tip the nearby path. Quantify:
       Candidate A is cap-DECREASING (Δic = -0.382 ff). Upstream load
       REDUCES — nearby paths through the upstream cone get FASTER, not
       slower. Sibling-tip risk: essentially ZERO for cap-decreasing
       upsizes. ✓ SAFE.
     If the upsize were cap-INCREASING (e.g. AO21x1 → AO21x2 with +0.002 ff),
     the same check would compare predicted ΔWNS_target against the
     worst_nearby_slack_ps headroom before committing.
  COST: 1 command. SAFETY: input_cap decreases, upstream is faster, no cascade.

CANDIDATE B: eco_clone_gate_worst_half place7069  (1.3: split fanout 10 → 5+5)
  A. Original cell_d = 23.34ps at load 17.17ff. After clone each driver sees
     ~half load (~8.5ff). For BUFx8, cell_d at 8.5ff ≈ 12-14ps → Δ ≈ -10ps
  B. UPSTREAM (place7071/Y at stage 1.2) — currently drives input_cap of
     place7069 only (~0.915ff). After clone it drives BOTH place7069 AND
     eco_clone_place7069 inputs → load DOUBLES from 0.915 → 1.83ff.
     place7071's cell_delay increases by K2 × 0.915ff ≈ +1.5ps.
  C. Wire delay: the original 29.43um wire is replaced by two ~half-length
     wires (one per clone), each driving ~5 sinks. Each new wire_d ≈ 5-6ps
     (vs original 11.57). Δwire ≈ -5ps for the moved sinks; the other half
     still sees the original ~11.57 → mixed. Net effect on path 1: depends on
     which half its sink falls into. Worst case +0 wire change.
  D. out_slew on clone branches improves; next stage cascade ≈ -1ps
  Net Δslack: +10 (cell) -1.5 (upstream) +0 (wire, best case) +1 (slew) = +9.5ps
  COST: 1 command (clone). SAFETY: structural move; must run in ISOLATION
  (no other commands this iter). Predict generously then OBSERVE before stacking.
  CALIBRATION WARNING: from <prediction_calibration>, clone predictions have
  averaged 5-20x optimistic. Derate +9.5 → +1-2ps actual is more realistic.

CANDIDATE C: eco_resize_gate _31348_ AND3x2_ASAP7_75t_SL  (1.8: L → SL VT swap)
  A. Δcell_delay: L→SL on same drive strength typically -2 to -5ps. Conservative -3ps.
  B. Upstream load: input_cap goes from 0.614ff (L) to 0.638ff (SL). +0.024ff.
     Negligible (less than 5% of any reasonable upstream load) → ~0ps cascade
  C. No wire change
  D. No meaningful slew change
  Net Δslack: +3ps on path 1
  Same shared cone? Need to check stage 1.8's on_other_violating_paths.
  If oovp=4 → +12ps effective TNS. If oovp=1 → +3ps TNS only.

CANDIDATE D: eco_resize_gate _31350_ INVx1_ASAP7_75t_SL  (1.11: L → SL)
  Same arithmetic as C. ~+2-3ps with negligible cascade.

CANDIDATE E: eco_resize_gate _19545_ AO22x1_ASAP7_75t_SL  (1.12: L → SL)
  Same arithmetic. ~+2-3ps.

CANDIDATE F: eco_insert_buffer on the 29um wire at stage 1.3
  Insert BUFx8 (cell_delay at this load ≈ 12ps; input_cap = 0.915ff).
  Removes ~half the wire_d for sinks moved behind the new buffer: Δwire = -6ps.
  BUT adds the buffer's intrinsic cell_delay: +12ps.
  Net for those sinks: -6 +12 = +6ps WORSE than original.
  DECISION: REJECT — buffer's intrinsic delay exceeds the wire delay we save.
  Rule of thumb (the user's engineering principle):
    "If buffer_delay > load_contribution_it_drives, the buffer is unnecessary."
    Here buffer_delay (12) > wire_saving (6) → DON'T insert.

CANDIDATE G: eco_remove_buffer place7068  (1.4: BUFx6f, moderate load — tricky case)
  Removal-candidate check (the 3 conditions from AGENTS.md):
    load_cap = 3.70 ff   (FAILS: > 2.0 ff threshold)
    cell_delay = 18.54 ps (passes)
    fanout = 4            (FAILS: > 2)
  At fanout=4 and load=3.7 ff, this buffer is actively isolating slew for 4 sinks.
  Removing it sends the upstream 41 ps in_slew downstream uncleaned → slew-cascade
  penalties on stages 1.5, 1.6.
  DECISION: SKIP — load and fanout both above the safe-removal thresholds.

CANDIDATE G2: eco_remove_buffer output1902  (last stage: BUFx2_SL driving primary output)
  Removal-candidate check:
    load_cap = 0.47 ff   (passes: < 2.0)
    cell_delay = 13.71 ps (passes: > 10)
    fanout = 1            (passes: <= 2)
  All three conditions met — strong removal candidate.
  Cascade arithmetic:
    A. Δcell_delay: -13.71 ps (buffer fully removed from path)
    B. Upstream (the cell driving output1902/A) sees +0.47 ff load
       minus the buffer's removed input_cap (~0.290 ff for BUFx2_SL)
       Net upstream Δload = +0.18 ff   (tiny)
       Upstream cell_delay penalty: ~K2 × 0.18 ff ≈ +0.5 ps
    C. No wire delay change (no net topology change; sinks already on direct net)
    D. Out_slew at the primary output: upstream now drives it directly. If upstream
       is a reasonable-strength cell, out_slew degrades modestly (maybe +5-10 ps)
       but PRIMARY OUTPUTS don't have downstream cells to cascade-poison.
  Net Δslack: +13.71 - 0.5 = +13.2 ps (raw Liberty estimate)
  Calibration: structural moves bucket is `no data` or thin → trust raw with 5x
  pessimism → honest estimate +13.2 / 5 = +2.6 ps.
  COST: 1 command (structural-isolation rule: this iter contains only removes).
  SAFETY: output1902 drives only the output port (load=0.47 ff). Upstream load
  barely changes. No downstream cell to poison via slew cascade. This is a
  physically safe removal.
  COMMIT this move.

  Note: 5 of the path 1 output-stage buffers (output1902/4/5/12/15) and one
  chain-end buffer (place6381 BUFx3, fanout=2, load=1.43 ff, cd=14.33 ps) all
  meet the three removal conditions. Commit one per iter (structural-isolation)
  so each removal's actual ΔWNS can be measured cleanly in next iter's
  <previous_target_path>.

CANDIDATE H: eco_insert_buffer for SLEW CLEANUP  (worked example)
  When it applies: STEP 4 flagged an unfixable slew SOURCE (upstream cell has
  upsize=[] AND vt_swap=[] — e.g. an FA/HA, a dont_touch hardmacro, or a tiny
  logic cell at the smallest drive in the library) whose out_slew is bad
  (>= 40 ps) AND that slew is feeding 2+ slew-sensitive downstream stages
  (FA, HA, complex AOI/OAI, AND/OR3-4-5, INV/BUF) whose cell_delay is inflated.

  DO NOT confuse with Candidate F. F handles a long wire (wire_delay > buffer
  intrinsic; you insert a buffer to SHORTEN the wire RC). H handles a clean wire
  but a degraded EDGE (you insert a buffer to REGENERATE the slew). The trigger
  data is different — H fires when wire_length is short (< 20 um) but in_slew
  is large because the upstream cell's out_slew is intrinsically degraded.

  Worked numbers (real Liberty values from <cell_delay_reference>):

    Upstream:  HAxp5_SL (an adder primitive, unfixable: upsize=[], vt_swap=[])
               Stage delay 42.5 ps, OUT_SLEW = 54 ps  ← the dirty edge

    Direct path (NO buffer inserted):
      Stage k+1: INVx2_SL  load=2.5 ff, in_slew=54 ps
        Liberty INVx2_SL @ (2.5 ff, is=80): cd ≈ 12.5 ps, out_slew ≈ 30 ps
        Liberty INVx2_SL @ (2.5 ff, is=30): cd ≈ 8.5 ps,  out_slew ≈ 21 ps
        Linear interp at is=54:           cd ≈ 10.3 ps, out_slew ≈ 25 ps
      Stage k+2: NAND2x2_SL load=2.0 ff, in_slew=25 ps (cleaner now, but still tax)
        Liberty cd ≈ 8.6 ps (at clean is=10 it would be ≈ 7.2 ps)
      Stage k+3: AOI21x1_SL load=1.8 ff, in_slew=22 ps (still slightly degraded)
        Liberty cd ≈ 13.0 ps (at clean is=10 it would be ≈ 11.4 ps)
      Total cd over the 3 downstream stages: 10.3 + 8.6 + 13.0 = 31.9 ps

    Inserted-buffer path:  insert BUFx4f_SL between HAxp5 and INVx2
      BUFx4f_SL @ (L_buf_out = INVx2.ic ≈ 1.07 ff + small wire ≈ 1.5 ff, is=54 ps):
        Liberty BUFx4f_SL @ (1.5 ff, is=30): cd = 15.3 ps, out_slew = 7 ps
        Liberty BUFx4f_SL @ (1.5 ff, is=80): cd = 20.5 ps, out_slew = 10 ps
        Linear interp at is=54: cd ≈ 17.8 ps, OUT_SLEW ≈ 8 ps  ← clean!
      Now INVx2_SL sees in_slew=8 ps (clean):
        Liberty INVx2_SL @ (2.5 ff, is=10): cd ≈ 6.6 ps, out_slew ≈ 11 ps
      NAND2x2_SL sees in_slew=11 ps (still clean):
        Liberty cd ≈ 7.2 ps
      AOI21x1_SL sees in_slew=~10 ps:
        Liberty cd ≈ 11.4 ps
      Total cd over inserted buffer + 3 downstream stages: 17.8 + 6.6 + 7.2 + 11.4
                                                         = 43.0 ps

    Net comparison:
      Direct:    31.9 ps
      Inserted:  43.0 ps
      Net Δ:     +11.1 ps WORSE  ← insertion LOSES here even with 3 downstream sinks

    DECISION: REJECT for this 3-sink case. The slew penalty on the INSERTED buffer
    (~18 ps at in_slew=54 ps) exceeds the slew-tax savings on 3 downstream cells
    (~6 ps total). For BUFx4f_SL to pay off, you need either:
      (a) 5+ downstream slew-sensitive stages reached before slew degrades again
          (rare in practice), OR
      (b) Downstream stage 1 is an FA/HA chain with multiple stages whose
          cell_delay drops ≥ 10 ps each when in_slew goes 54 → 8 ps
          (Liberty FA D(is=80) − D(is=10) gap is the deciding number).

  Variant H2 (when H DOES commit): the upstream slew source feeds an FA→FA→HA
  chain (3 adder primitives in a row, all paying steep K1 slew tax).
    If FAx1 at (load=1.5 ff, is=10) gives cd≈A and FAx1 at (load=1.5 ff, is=80)
    gives cd≈B with B − A ≥ 12 ps (look up your actual numbers — FA cells often
    show 20-30 ps spread), then cleaning the slew at the chain head saves
    ≥ 3 × 12 = 36 ps downstream while paying ~18 ps for the inserted buffer.
    Net ≈ +18 ps. THAT case COMMITS — and it is the case to look for whenever
    you see a multi-stage FA/HA run with consistently high in_slew (≥ 40 ps).

  Commit checklist (before emitting an eco_insert_buffer for slew cleanup):
    1. Upstream slew source has upsize=[] AND vt_swap=[] (otherwise fix
       upstream — cleaner; no new cell on the path).
    2. Upstream out_slew_ps ≥ 40 ps (no point cleaning a 25 ps edge).
    3. At least 3 downstream slew-sensitive cells whose Liberty rows show
       D(is=80) − D(is=10) ≥ 8 ps each (cells that pay the slew tax heavily).
    4. Liberty lookup for chosen BUF at (L_buf_out, in_slew) shows out_slew
       ≤ 15 ps (if buffer is too small for in_slew, its out_slew stays dirty —
       escalate to BUFx6f/x8/x12 or skip).
    5. Computed Σ ΔD_k > B_d + 5 ps headroom for calibration uncertainty.
    6. PREVIOUS NEGATIVE ATTEMPTS DO NOT BLOCK THIS MOVE if any commit
       checklist condition above has flipped since the prior attempt (different
       BUF size; different target net; downstream chain composition changed).
       State explicitly in Why-vs-alternatives WHICH checklist item differs
       from the prior rejection.

  Tcl recipe pattern (the inserted buffer's NAME must be unique in the
  netlist — prefix with eco_slewclean_ to avoid collisions):

    set _net [get_name [get_nets -of_objects [get_pins {<slew_src>/Y_or_SN}]]]
    eco_insert_buffer $_net <slew_src>/<output_pin> <BUF_cell> \
        eco_slewclean_<unique_tag> -at centroid

  Structural-isolation: counts as a structural move. Emit ONLY this command
  (or this + one other on the same net) per iter so its actual ΔWNS can be
  measured cleanly in next iter's <previous_target_path>. NO concurrent
  eco_resize_gate on the same path.

## STEP 5.5 — Batch-interaction math (if proposing >=2 moves)
After computing per-move Δslack, do NOT just sum them for the iter ΔWNS.
WNS = the slack of the worst-violating endpoint (the most-negative signed
slack across all paths). Once you push the rank-1 path past the rank-2
path slack, the rank-2 path becomes the new WNS holder and further gains
on the original rank-1 only help TNS, not WNS.

Three effects to apply when batching moves:

(A) WNS-SATURATION (the dominant one):
    - Look at <iteration_context> path[1].slack_ps and path[2].slack_ps.
      The DIFFERENCE is your max headroom for same-cone gains. e.g.:
          path[1].slack_ps = -275.81  path[2].slack_ps = -274.66
          headroom = |path[1] - path[2]| = 1.15 ps
      Even if 4 swaps individually predict +3 ps each (sum = +12 ps), your
      WNS gain this iter is capped at ~+1.15 ps. The remaining +10.85 ps
      lands in TNS only (cleans up path 1 further but does not move WNS).
    - Saturated batch ΔWNS = MIN(sum_of_per_move_deltas, headroom_to_path2)
    - (Don't confuse: <nearby_endpoints> starts at rank 6 — path[2] is in
      <iteration_context> detailed path[] block, NOT in nearby_endpoints.)

(B) CASCADE COMPOUNDING (occasional bonus):
    - If two adjacent VT swaps both target path 1: swap A produces cleaner
      out_slew, swap B then sees a better in_slew (look in
      <cell_delay_reference>: same load, lower in_slew → lower cell_delay).
      This means swap B actual gain may EXCEED its solo prediction.
    - This is positive noise — gives a 10-30% bonus on top of saturated cap.

(C) LOAD CASCADE (cap-INCREASING upsize batches — danger zone):
    - N upsizes on the same upstream chain each add Δinput_cap.
    - Cumulative upstream load delta = sum of Δic across upsizes sharing
      an upstream driver.
    - Upstream cell_delay penalty ≈ K2 × cumulative_Δic. For BUFx, K2~3-5 ps/ff.
    - If cumulative Δic > 1 ff on a shared upstream, the batch can NET NEGATIVE.
    - Cap-DECREASING upsizes (e.g. BUFx6f → BUFx8 has lower input_cap) are
      the inverse: cumulative cap reduces upstream load → bonus.

Worked example (the 4-swap batch from Candidate A + C/D/E):
  Per-move Liberty Δslack: +2.1 (A) +3 (C) +3 (D) +3 (E) = +11.1 ps raw sum.
  Hypothetical tight-headroom case (NOT this example's numbers; here
  path[1]=-285.55, path[2]=-284.74 so headroom is only ~0.8 ps): suppose
  path[1].slack=-78.5, path[2].slack=-76.5 → headroom = |-78.5-(-76.5)| = 2.0 ps.
  Saturated batch ΔWNS = MIN(+11.1, +2.0) = +2.0 ps.
  The other +9.1 ps lives in TNS — cleans up path 1 behind WNS-rank-1 but
  does not move WNS further.
  Apply calibration from <prediction_calibration>. If bucket
  `eco_resize_gate (batch_4+)` shows mean_ratio=0.04 →
    honest ΔWNS = +2.0 × 0.04 = +0.08 ps.
  If that is below the cost-benefit gate, ROTATE to picking one cell per
  path[1..5] instead — same 4 swaps, different cones, additive WNS.

Rule of thumb:
  N moves on the SAME cone   ≈ headroom-to-path2 (saturated, then derated)
  N moves on DIFFERENT cones ≈ N × per-move (additive, full per-move ratio)
So a 4-swap batch on 4 different paths is typically 3-5× better than 4 swaps
on the same path — at the same Liberty-computed raw sum.

## STEP 6 — Cost/benefit comparison and final pick
Rank by (expected Δslack × shared-cone multiplier × confidence / risk):

  Candidate            move type     pred Δslack (path1)   shared cone mult     confidence
  A place7071→BUFx8    resize         +2.1 ps              ×4 (shared)          high
  B clone place7069    structural     +9.5 ps (derated +2) ×4 (shared)          LOW (cascade volatile)
  C _31348_ VT swap    resize         +3 ps                ×4 if shared         very high
  D _31350_ VT swap    resize         +2-3 ps              ×4 if shared         very high
  E _19545_ VT swap    resize         +2-3 ps              ×4 if shared         very high
  F insert_buffer 1.3  structural     -6 ps  (REJECT)      —                    —
  G remove place7068   structural     +15ps (uncertain)    ×4                   medium (slew risk)

Decision: pick A + C + D + E (4 commands, all eco_resize_gate, all high
confidence, all on shared cone). Skip B (clone predictions historically wrong),
skip F (arithmetic shows it loses), skip G (slew-cascade risk warrants a query
tool before committing).

This is a pure-resize iter (no structural moves), so MAX_COMMANDS budget can
go higher. But 4 carefully-justified moves > 5 less-justified ones — keep it tight.

## STEP 7 — Write the predictions HONESTLY and emit the Tcl recipe
In the Move plan table the Δslack est. must be the model's BEST GUESS for the
actual measured ΔWNS (not the cascade-arithmetic raw number). Apply calibration:

  Calibration block (from prior iters) shows resize ratio ≈ 0.06.
  So raw_estimate × 0.06 = honest_prediction
    A: +2.1 raw → +0.1 honest (but VT swaps & cap-decreasing upsizes calibrate
                                better; use 0.4 ratio → +0.8 honest)
    C/D/E: +3 raw VT-swap → ×0.4 (better calibration) → +1.2 honest each
  Predicted WNS gain this iter: ~0.8 + 1.2 + 1.2 + 1.2 = ~4.4 ps
  If actual comes back at +1 ps total → resize calibration is even worse than
  0.4 — record and derate further next iter.

## Tcl recipe (the actual commands to emit)
```tcl
eco_resize_gate place7071 BUFx8_ASAP7_75t_SL
eco_resize_gate _31348_ AND3x2_ASAP7_75t_SL
eco_resize_gate _31350_ INVx1_ASAP7_75t_SL
eco_resize_gate _19545_ AO22x1_ASAP7_75t_SL
```

## STEP 8 — After re-timing, audit the prediction
On the NEXT iter, you will see in <previous_target_path> the same path
re-reported. Compare:

  - Did stage 1.2's cell_delay drop from 18.75 to ~17.4 as predicted (Δ≈-1.3)?
      If yes: candidate A's prediction was accurate. Keep using this reasoning.
      If no (e.g., still 17): the BUFx8 vs BUFx6f scaling ratio was wrong for
      this load regime. Update mental model.
  - Did the path's overall slack improve by the predicted ~4.4ps?
      If yes: confidence in the cascade arithmetic holds.
      If much less: the next-stage slew/cascade was not what was assumed.
  - Did any sibling path move? Check siblings[] vs prior iter.

This audit is what closes the learning loop. Without it, you predict from
memorized formulas forever and never adapt to THIS design's actual response.

## ANTI-PATTERNS — do NOT do these
A. Don't downgrade VT in a resize. _SL → _L is a slowdown, never useful for
   setup-WNS recovery. (Iter 16 of a prior run did this by accident, lost 12ps.)

B. Don't clone a clone. Targets starting with "eco_clone_" are already split;
   further cloning just adds more buffer instances to the chain.

C. Don't clone a buffer (BUFx*, INVx*). A buffer's job is to drive load;
   cloning ADDS a new buffer cell delay to half the paths. Upsize the buffer
   instead (more drive strength → faster) if its load is too high.

D. Don't batch a structural move with resizes. If you emit eco_insert_buffer
   or eco_clone_gate_worst_half or eco_remove_buffer, that iter contains
   ONLY structural moves so you can attribute the ΔWNS cleanly next iter.

E. Don't trust your raw predictions. The <prediction_calibration> block shows
   your historical ratio. If it's 0.05, your "+10ps" prediction is really
   "+0.5ps" — derate before deciding if a move is worth emitting.

F. Trust the dont_touch column in path[] — it is the authoritative source.
   A cell is untouchable if AND ONLY IF dont_touch=true in its path[] row.
   Do NOT infer "untouchable" from the hierarchical name (e.g. paths through
   HAN_CARLSON / KOGGE_STONE / BRENT_KUNG adders contain many NORMAL cells
   with dont_touch=false that CAN be modified when their upsize/vt_swap
   columns show options). Per-row columns decide availability, not naming —
   see AGENTS.md (ARITHMETIC PRIMITIVE RULE) for the column semantics.

   Genuinely untouchable cells (will have dont_touch=true in path[]):
     - All DFF/LATCH (is_dff=true)
     - Clock buffers / clock-tree cells (per netlist + dont_touch flag)
     - Black-box macros (SRAM, IP blocks)
     - User-specified dont_touch instances (set by synthesis constraints)
   For these: skip categorically. For everything else, trust the columns.
